{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17500029","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17500029"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:07:13+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:07:13+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1601"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1601","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1601"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.49,0.24,0.18,0.07,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1601"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44071"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1601","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1601"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1601"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29052"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"452"},{"type":"tags","id":"2195"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5224"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6738"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44071","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/44071"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn otherwise healthy 35-year-old man presents to his General Practitioner with a six-month history of painless lumps on his scrotum. They were first noticed incidentally in the shower. He has a medical history of an orchiopexy for an undescended testis as an infant. He takes no regular medications. He is a non-smoker. On examination, two masses are observed (Image). The masses are compressible, regular and are 0.5-1 cm in diameter and appear to arise independent of the testis.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Epidermoid cysts","Epididymal cysts","Lipomas","Testicular cancer","Donovanosis"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThese are \u003Cstrong\u003Eepidermoid cysts\u003C/strong\u003E. Whilst these lesions - otherwise know as sebaceous cysts - are more typically found on the trunk, they can occur anywhere on the body, and the scrotum is one such site. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEpididymal cysts\u003C/strong\u003E arise from the epididymis and these lesions would not be so obvious. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELipomas\u003C/strong\u003E can be found anywhere on the body - but the scrotum would be a very unusual site - \u00a0and the lesions would not be so well defined. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDonovanosis\u003C/strong\u003E produces ulcerating lesions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETesticular cancer\u003C/strong\u003E is a possibility and should be ruled out especially given the history of undescended testis, which is a risk factor for testicular cancer. However such masses are more likely to be incompressible, irregular and arising from within the testis itself.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Testicular cancer should always be ruled out with presentation of a scrotal mass, a thorough history and examination is essential in the diagnostic process."],"references":["Junnila J, Lassen P. Testicular masses. Am Fam Physician. 1998 Feb 15;57(4):685-92. Available at: https://www.aafp.org/pubs/afp/issues/1998/0215/p685.html#:~:text=A%20testicular%20tumor%20usually%20presents,suspicion%20of%20underlying%20testicular%20cancer.","Gaddam SJ, Chesnut GT. Testicle Cancer. In: StatPearls [Online]. 2022. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK563159/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29052"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1601"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"16848"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"16848","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/16848"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/e75661e2-350a-4e56-942d-0f4b7920e996.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/e75661e2-350a-4e56-942d-0f4b7920e996.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":800,"height":600}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29052","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/29052"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-04-06T12:11:23+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-04-06T12:11:23+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1601"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44071"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"36","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/36"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd43","name":"Urology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"452","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/t